s take away bodies. Families aren't given the chance to say goodbye to their loved ones. Because the virus is transmitted through touch, it overrides the basic human need for contact and connection. In this picture, health care workers hold hands and pray before doing the risky work of entering an Ebola isolation ward. They find a way to connect despite the layers of latex. No one wants to be alone when facing Ebola. I'm not a religious person. At times like this though, there's little to do but hold hands and pray for each other.\"","slug":"ebolastaffing","caption":"<b>Glenna Gordon,  Sept. 29, 2014. Monrovia, Liberia.<br><br><\/b>\"Ebola is a disease that divides husband and wife, mother and child, doctor and patient. Health care workers in protective gear that look like space suits attend to patients. Men with chlorine spray-cans take away bodies. Families aren't given the chance to say goodbye to their loved ones. Because the virus is transmitted through touch, it overrides the basic human need for contact and connection. In this picture, health care workers hold hands and pray before doing the risky work of entering an Ebola isolation ward. They find a way to connect despite the layers of latex. No one wants to be alone when facing Ebola. I'm not a religious person. At times like this though, there's little to do but hold hands and pray for each other.\"\n","credit":"Glenna Gordon\u2014The Wall Street Journal","alt":"EBOLASTAFFING","width":3000,"height":2000,"orientation":"square","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3507162\/inside-ebola-crisis-moving-photographs\/photo\/ebolastaffing\/","encoded_url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3507162\/inside-ebola-crisis-moving-photographs\/photo\/ebolastaffing\/","twitter_via":"TIMEHealth","encoded_title":"Inside+the+Ebola+Crisis%3A+The+Images+that+Moved+them+Most","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3507162%2Finside-ebola-crisis-moving-photographs%2Fphoto%2Febolastaffing%2F","twitter_encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3507